<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n54119e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54119e">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54119e"> 119(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> shrine of Mt Mu, <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54119e"><li>FW 51.19f </li><li><a href="../../flex/c/lexc.htm#n54119e">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/c/l39c.htm#n54119e">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54119e">MS BL 47476a-171</ms> </li><li>JJA 49:363 <a name="cd10" href="../../FF/fdra/cda.htm#cd10">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/c/cd10.htm#n54119e">Draft: I.3&sect;1.10</a>/2.10/3.10</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Although the ceremony of praying at shrines and offering sacrifices to ensure the birth of a son had invariably been the affair of women, who were more directly responsible in the matter, Kung the Tall <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> at length selected a <mark>shrine</mark> of sound reputation on a hill which was <mark>known as Mount Mu</mark> and went there to pray with the young wife, adding his supplications to hers. <small> Carl Crow, <a name="CCMK" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#CCMK"><cite title="source">Master Kung. The Story of Confucius</cite></a> (Sep 1937) 30</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Old Kung the Tall, having divorced his wife, had married a fifteen-year-old girl. </mm> </dd></dl>
